^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|On close decisions, I use Quick Tricks to decide whether or not my hand is a bit better than Bergen hand evaluation tells me it is. Here is my methodology. There are a max of 8 quick tricks and there are 40 HCP. Therefore, on average, each 5 HCP (40 / 8) should contain 1 quick trick. Hands with above average quick trick count are better than their HCP indicate. |
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

So,  for example, if I have 12 HCP, on average I should have about 2.5 quick tricks. If my hand contains, for example, 3 quick tricks, then it is probably worth more than 12 HCP and I will stretch on close decisions. On the other hand, if it has only 2 quick tricks, I will be conservative. This is particularly useful on slam decisions, where an abundance of Aces and Kings is particularly important.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

I also use Quick Tricks for the Bergen 4 and 4 rule. When I have a balanced 22-24 HCP points I open 2@C intending to bid 2N over partner's response. However, with distributional 20+ HCP and when a major suit contract is the likely auction I use the "9 trick" rule and/or Bergen's "4 and 4" rule.
|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


ht|n|AT|The "9 trick rule" says I can open 2@C if I can count 9 tricks in my hand. For example with the hand shown on the left:|HT|o|cs|1|at|^b{|ih|pSA HAKJT542 C65 DAK6|at|}|ht|o|AT|^j@2I have 9 sure tricks|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


HC|SAHAKJT54DAK|AT| in my hand no matter what is partner's hand.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


LC|SAHAKJT54DAK|AT|

Marty Bergen uses the "4 and 4" rule. The rule says you should open 2@C if you have at least 4 Quick Tricks and no more than 4 losers. Quick Tricks are easy to count. They are basically the number of tricks you expect to take immediately in a suit. A= 1, AK= 2, Kx= �, AQ= 1 � KQ= 1. There can only be a maximum of 2 Quick Tricks in each suit. With the hand on the left I have 5 Quick Tricks.|hc|SAHAKDAK|at|-1 spade, 2 hearts, 2 diamond.|
